# Orbit Windows Shell Replacement - Implementation Plan

## Vision & Scope

### What We're Building
Orbit is a **complete replacement** for the Windows desktop environment. This is not a skin or overlay - it's a fundamental replacement of:
- **Explorer.exe** (desktop, taskbar, file manager)
- **DWM (Desktop Window Manager)** (window composition, effects, decorations)
- **Windows Shell** (the primary UI that starts after login)

When a user logs into Windows with Orbit installed, they will see ZERO Microsoft UI. Everything - from the desktop wallpaper to window title bars to the taskbar - is rendered by our GPUI-based UI.

### Why This Is Complex
This is an exceptionally challenging project because:

1. **DWM Replacement**: The Desktop Window Manager is deeply integrated into Windows. We must:
   - Disable the DWM service entirely
   - Implement our own compositor in GPUI
   - Handle ALL window composition, transparency, and visual effects
   - Capture and render every application window's content within custom decorations

2. **Window Management**: Every application launched by the user will create windows expecting native Windows decorations. We must:
   - Hook ALL window creation events system-wide
   - Remove native frames/decorations from every window
   - Draw custom title bars, buttons, and borders in GPUI
   - Route window messages (move, resize, close, minimize) to our system
   - Maintain perfect synchronization between window content and decorations

3. **System Integration**: We're replacing core Windows components, which means:
   - Registry modification to set ourselves as the shell
   - Service management to disable Explorer and DWM
   - Handling all desktop responsibilities (file icons, right-click menus, wallpaper)
   - Process monitoring to catch new windows immediately

4. **Stability**: If our shell crashes, the user has NO UI. We must be rock-solid.

## Architecture Overview

### Components

#### 1. orbit-core (Shared Library)
**Purpose**: Common types, IPC protocol, and utilities used by all other components.

**Responsibilities**:
- Define IPC message protocol (service ↔ UI communication)
- Window state types (position, size, decorations, z-order)
- Configuration structures
- Error types and result wrappers
- Logging setup and utilities

**Key Types**:
```rust
struct WindowInfo {
    hwnd: HWND,
    process_id: u32,
    title: String,
    bounds: Rectangle,
    state: WindowState,  // Normal, Minimized, Maximized, Fullscreen
    has_custom_decorations: bool,
}

enum IpcMessage {
    WindowCreated(WindowInfo),
    WindowDestroyed(HWND),
    WindowMoved(HWND, Point),
    WindowResized(HWND, Size),
    ServiceStatus(ServiceState),
}
```

#### 2. orbit-wm (Window Manager Library)
**Purpose**: Low-level window management - the dirty work of hooking and manipulating windows.

**Responsibilities**:
- Install system-wide window hooks (SetWindowsHookEx with WH_CBT)
- Intercept window creation BEFORE it's visible
- Remove window decorations (WS_CAPTION, WS_THICKFRAME, etc.)
- Track all windows in a thread-safe registry
- Handle window message routing
- Provide API for z-order management

**Technical Deep Dive - Window Hooking**:
```rust
// When ANY process creates a window, Windows calls our hook:
unsafe extern "system" fn cbt_hook_proc(
    code: i32, 
    wparam: WPARAM, 
    lparam: LPARAM
) -> LRESULT {
    if code == HCBT_CREATEWND {
        let hwnd = HWND(wparam.0 as isize);
        
        // Remove native decorations IMMEDIATELY
        let style = GetWindowLongW(hwnd, GWL_STYLE);
        let new_style = style & !(WS_CAPTION | WS_THICKFRAME | WS_SYSMENU);
        SetWindowLongW(hwnd, GWL_STYLE, new_style);
        
        // Notify orbit-ui via IPC
        send_ipc(IpcMessage::WindowCreated(get_window_info(hwnd)));
    }
    CallNextHookEx(None, code, wparam, lparam)
}
```

**Key Features**:
- Global hook injection (affects ALL processes)
- Window state tracking (HashMap<HWND, WindowInfo>)
- Safe Rust wrapper around unsafe Windows APIs
- Thread-safe access (Arc<RwLock<WindowRegistry>>)

#### 3. orbit-service (Windows Service)
**Purpose**: System-level operations requiring SYSTEM privileges.

**Responsibilities**:
- Run as a Windows service (auto-start at boot)
- Disable conflicting services (Explorer, DWM)
- Install/uninstall window hooks via orbit-wm
- Manage registry (set/restore shell)
- IPC server for orbit-ui
- Process monitoring (watch for new applications)
- Emergency recovery (if orbit-ui crashes, restart or restore Explorer)

**Service Management**:
```rust
// Disable DWM - this is CRITICAL
fn disable_dwm() -> Result<()> {
    let scm = OpenSCManagerW(None, None, SC_MANAGER_ALL_ACCESS)?;
    let service = OpenServiceW(scm, "dwm", SERVICE_ALL_ACCESS)?;
    
    // Stop DWM
    ControlService(service, SERVICE_CONTROL_STOP, &mut SERVICE_STATUS::default())?;
    
    // Set to disabled so it doesn't restart
    ChangeServiceConfigW(
        service,
        SERVICE_NO_CHANGE,
        SERVICE_DISABLED,  // Disable permanently
        // ... other params
    )?;
    
    Ok(())
}
```

**Registry Management**:
```rust
// Set Orbit as the Windows shell
fn set_shell() -> Result<()> {
    let key = RegOpenKeyExW(
        HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE,
        "SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows NT\\CurrentVersion\\Winlogon",
        // ...
    )?;
    
    // Backup original value
    let original = RegGetValueW(key, "Shell")?;
    RegSetValueExW(key, "Shell.backup", original)?;
    
    // Set Orbit
    RegSetValueExW(key, "Shell", "C:\\Path\\To\\orbit-ui.exe")?;
    
    Ok(())
}
```

**IPC Server**:
- Named pipe server listening for orbit-ui connections
- Bidirectional communication
- Sends window creation/destruction events
- Receives compositor requests from UI

#### 4. orbit-ui (Main UI Application)
**Purpose**: The actual desktop environment users see and interact with.

**Responsibilities**:
- Initialize WGPUI application
- Implement compositor (render all windows)
- Draw custom window decorations
- Render desktop (wallpaper, icons, widgets)
- Render taskbar
- Handle user input (mouse, keyboard)
- IPC client to orbit-service
- Window management UI (Alt+Tab, snap assist, etc.)

**Compositor Architecture**:
```rust
struct OrbitCompositor {
    windows: Vec<ComposedWindow>,
    desktop: DesktopLayer,
    taskbar: TaskbarLayer,
    overlay: OverlayLayer,  // tooltips, context menus, etc.
}

struct ComposedWindow {
    hwnd: HWND,
    content: CapturedContent,  // BitBlt'd window content
    decorations: CustomDecorations,  // Title bar, buttons, border
    bounds: Rectangle,
    z_index: i32,
}

impl OrbitCompositor {
    fn render(&self, cx: &mut gpui::Context) {
        // Layer 1: Desktop (wallpaper, icons)
        self.desktop.render(cx);
        
        // Layer 2: Windows (back to front by z_index)
        for window in &self.windows.sort_by_z_index() {
            // Render custom title bar
            window.decorations.render(cx);
            
            // Render captured window content
            cx.draw_texture(window.content.texture, window.bounds);
        }
        
        // Layer 3: Taskbar (always on top)
        self.taskbar.render(cx);
        
        // Layer 4: Overlay (tooltips, menus)
        self.overlay.render(cx);
    }
}
```

**Window Content Capture**:
```rust
// Capture window content to render in GPUI
fn capture_window_content(hwnd: HWND) -> Result<Texture> {
    // Get window DC
    let hdc = GetDC(hwnd);
    let mem_dc = CreateCompatibleDC(hdc);
    
    // Create bitmap
    let (width, height) = get_window_size(hwnd);
    let bitmap = CreateCompatibleBitmap(hdc, width, height);
    SelectObject(mem_dc, bitmap);
    
    // Copy window content
    BitBlt(mem_dc, 0, 0, width, height, hdc, 0, 0, SRCCOPY);
    
    // Convert to GPU texture
    let pixels = get_bitmap_pixels(bitmap);
    let texture = cx.create_texture_from_pixels(pixels, width, height);
    
    // Cleanup
    ReleaseDC(hwnd, hdc);
    DeleteDC(mem_dc);
    DeleteObject(bitmap);
    
    Ok(texture)
}
```

**Custom Window Decorations**:
```rust
struct WindowDecorations {
    title_bar: TitleBar,
    border: Border,
}

struct TitleBar {
    title: String,
    icon: Option<Texture>,
    buttons: Vec<TitleBarButton>,  // Minimize, Maximize, Close
    height: f32,
    drag_area: Rectangle,
}

impl TitleBar {
    fn render(&self, cx: &mut gpui::Context, window_bounds: Rectangle) {
        let title_bar_bounds = Rectangle {
            x: window_bounds.x,
            y: window_bounds.y,
            width: window_bounds.width,
            height: self.height,
        };
        
        // Background
        cx.fill_rect(title_bar_bounds, Color::from_hex("#1e1e1e"));
        
        // Icon
        if let Some(icon) = &self.icon {
            cx.draw_texture(icon, /* ... */);
        }
        
        // Title text
        cx.draw_text(&self.title, /* ... */);
        
        // Buttons (minimize, maximize, close)
        for button in &self.buttons {
            button.render(cx);
        }
    }
    
    fn handle_click(&mut self, point: Point) -> Option<WindowAction> {
        // Check if click is on buttons
        for button in &self.buttons {
            if button.bounds.contains(point) {
                return Some(button.action);
            }
        }
        
        // Check if in drag area
        if self.drag_area.contains(point) {
            return Some(WindowAction::StartDrag);
        }
        
        None
    }
}
```

## Critical Technical Challenges

### Challenge 1: Window Content Updates
**Problem**: When an application redraws its content (e.g., video playing, text being typed), we need to capture and display those updates in real-time.

**Solution Options**:
1. **Polling with BitBlt**: Capture window content every frame (16ms for 60fps)
   - Pros: Simple, works with all applications
   - Cons: CPU intensive, may miss updates

2. **WM_PAINT Hooking**: Hook WM_PAINT messages to know when to recapture
   - Pros: More efficient, update only when needed
   - Cons: Some apps bypass WM_PAINT

3. **DWM Shared Surfaces**: Use DWM APIs to access the window's GPU texture
   - Pros: Zero-copy, GPU efficient
   - Cons: Complex, requires DWM to be partially running

**Recommended**: Start with Option 1 (polling), optimize to Option 3 later.

### Challenge 2: Input Routing
**Problem**: User clicks on a window we're rendering. How do we send that input to the actual application?

**Solution**:
```rust
fn handle_mouse_click(&self, point: Point) {
    // Find which window was clicked
    let window = self.windows.iter()
        .find(|w| w.bounds.contains(point))
        .unwrap();
    
    // Check if click is on our decorations
    if window.decorations.bounds.contains(point) {
        // Handle decoration click (close button, drag, etc.)
        window.decorations.handle_click(point);
    } else {
        // Transform point to window-local coordinates
        let local_point = point - window.bounds.origin;
        
        // Send input to actual window
        unsafe {
            PostMessageW(
                window.hwnd,
                WM_LBUTTONDOWN,
                /* ... */
            );
        }
    }
}
```

### Challenge 3: Z-Order and Focus Management
**Problem**: Windows expects to control which window is on top and has focus. We need to maintain our own z-order while keeping Windows in sync.

**Solution**:
- Maintain our own z-order stack
- When user clicks a window, call `SetForegroundWindow` to sync with Windows
- Hook `SetWindowPos` to catch external z-order changes
- Use `WM_ACTIVATEAPP` to track focus changes

### Challenge 4: Full-Screen Applications
**Problem**: Games and video players expect exclusive full-screen access.

**Solution**:
- Detect full-screen windows (window size == screen size, no decorations)
- Switch to "pass-through" mode: hide our decorations, let app render directly
- Alternative: Render full-screen apps normally but with minimal overhead

### Challenge 5: Multi-Monitor Support
**Problem**: Windows can span multiple monitors with different DPIs.

**Solution**:
- Enumerate all displays with `EnumDisplayMonitors`
- Create separate GPUI windows for each monitor
- Track which windows belong to which monitor
- Handle window dragging between monitors
- Respect per-monitor DPI settings

## Data Flow Architecture

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                          Windows Kernel                          │
│  (Window creation events, process starts, input events)          │
└───────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                │
                ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                       orbit-wm (Hook DLL)                        │
│  • Installed system-wide via SetWindowsHookEx                    │
│  • Runs in EVERY process that creates windows                    │
│  • Strips decorations immediately on window creation             │
└───────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                │
                │ IPC (Named Pipe)
                ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                     orbit-service (Service)                      │
│  • Runs as SYSTEM (highest privileges)                           │
│  • Manages services (disable Explorer/DWM)                       │
│  • Aggregates window events from orbit-wm                        │
│  • Monitors process creation                                     │
└───────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                │
                │ IPC (Named Pipe)
                ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                       orbit-ui (UI Process)                      │
│  • Runs as current user                                          │
│  • GPUI application with compositor                              │
│  • Renders everything user sees                                  │
│  • Handles input, forwards to applications                       │
│                                                                   │
│  ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐   │
│  │                    Rendering Layers                       │   │
│  │  1. Desktop (wallpaper, icons)                            │   │
│  │  2. Windows (content + decorations, sorted by z-index)    │   │
│  │  3. Taskbar (always on top)                               │   │
│  │  4. Overlays (menus, tooltips, Alt+Tab)                   │   │
│  └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘   │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                │
                │ Windows APIs
                ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    Application Windows                           │
│  (Chrome, Notepad, VSCode, etc.)                                 │
│  • No decorations (stripped by orbit-wm)                         │
│  • Content captured by orbit-ui via BitBlt                       │
│  • Receive input via PostMessage from orbit-ui                   │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## Implementation Workplan

### Prerequisites Understanding
Before starting, the implementing agent MUST understand:
1. This is a SYSTEM-LEVEL shell replacement, not a user application
2. Bugs can make Windows unusable (always test in a VM first)
3. Window hooking affects EVERY process - memory leaks = system freeze
4. DWM disabling means we're responsible for ALL visual feedback

